[1] Cholera - Mexico (Hidalgo State)
Date: Mon 14 Jul 2013
Source: AM [in Spanish, transl., summ., edited]
http://www.am.com.mx/notareforma/55573


The Secretariat of Health of Hidalgo [State] confirmed 2 new cholera cases in the Municipality of Tlaxcoapan, where the previous week there were 3 cases of people infected with the cholera bacterium. The Assistant Secretary for Health of Hidalgo, Maria Dolores Osorio, confirmed in a press conference these 2 new cholera cases in the State, with which, there are now 5 people affected by the disease so far in 2014.

[Byline: Fernando Paniagua]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Recently 2 cases of the infection were also reported in Veracruz State. A map of Mexico showing the locations of the states of Veracruz and Hidalgo can be found at: http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Blank_map_of_Mexico_with_states_names.svg. A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Mexico is available at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2619526,14.

In a recently released report (MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep 2014; 63(25); 552-3 http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6325a5.htm?s_cid=mm6325a5_w) during 19 Sep 2013-15 Dec 2013, a total of 175 cases of cholera were confirmed in La Huasteca (159 in Hidalgo, 14 in Veracruz, and 2 in San Luis Potosi).

These cases and those of 2013 occurred in La Huasteca (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Huasteca) area, a geographical and cultural region located in Mexico along the Gulf of Mexico that includes parts of the states of Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Puebla, Hidalgo, San Luis Potosi, Queretaro, and Guanajuato. It is roughly defined as the area in which the Huastec people had influence when their civilization was at its height in the Mesoamerican period. Today, the Huastecs occupy only a fraction of this region, with the Nahua people now the most numerous indigenous group. - Mod.LL]

******
[2] Cholera - Benin (Atlantic District)
Date: Mon 14 Jul 2014
Source: Slate Afrique, AFP (Agence France-Press) report [in French, machine transl., edited]
http://www.slateafrique.com/496033/benin-une-epidemie-de-cholera-fait-7-morts


A cholera epidemic raging in southern Benin killed 7 out of 150 cases recently counted, the Minister of Health Services said Monday, 14 Jul 2014. "The epidemic (cholera) broke out in the health area of Allada-Ze-Toffo [the separate towns in the south] and has unfortunately already killed 7 people (...) of the 150 cases recorded," said Akoko Kinde Gazar to AFP.

"This is a disease that has quickly evolved due to the non-reporting of some cases. But today, 14 Jul 2014, we have taken steps to control the epidemic," Dr Didier Agbozognigbe, Coordinator of the infected health zone, told AFP.

