[4] Cholera, suspected - Nigeria (Plateau State)
Date: Mon 14 Jul 2014
Source: AllAfrica, Daily Trust report [edited]
http://allafrica.com/stories/201407141641.html


4 children of the same parents and 2 others have died, while several others are said to have been affected by an outbreak of a disease suspected to be cholera in Dangi town, Kanam Local Government Area of Plateau State.

Deputy Chairman of Kanam Local Government Area, who is also the Supervisory Counselor for Health, Umar Yakubu Albura, told newsmen at the weekend in Jos, that "the recent outbreak of cholera in Kanam has become a source of worry to the health department of the local government, because 3 days ago, 4 children of one family and 2 other adults died of cholera, and many others are already affected."

Albura added: "We are highly disturbed by the spread of profuse diarrhea and vomiting in Dengi and the surrounding villages. Although we received medical support from the state Ministry of Health in order to curtail spread of the disease, a good number of the affected persons prefer patronizing local health workers for treatment, rather than going to hospital, and that has a negative effect in coordinating and controlling the disease."

But Plateau State Epidemiologist, Dr Raymond Juryit, who led an outbreak investigation team and journalists to Dengi, said: "All the patients admitted were affected by malaria, typhoid and other tropical infections that are associated with diarrhea and vomiting, but it is not cholera. We have gone round to hospitals and clinics within Dengi town, including the General Hospital, but we could not establish a single case of cholera. All those we found had malaria, typhoid, shigella and other infections; 3 weeks ago, we received a report from our Disease Surveillance Officer in Dengi, and when we verified, 34 suspected cholera cases were recorded with one dead."

[Byline: Hassan Ibrahim]

